{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50fa9084-010a-4d27-8500-32dee1e0e099","content":"I can't analyze dump files directly, but here's how you can investigate your `.dmp` file:\n\n### Using `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful SOS commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Print last exception (start here!) |\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `gcroot <addr>` | Trace object references |\n\n### Using LLDB (Linux) or WinDbg (Windows)\nThese offer deeper native + managed debugging with the SOS extension.\n\n**Typical workflow:**\n1. Run `pe` to see the crashing exception and stack trace.\n2. Use `clrthreads` → switch threads → `clrstack` to inspect other threads.\n3. Use `dso` / `gcroot` to examine objects on the stack.\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9be6b7f9-9cdc-47cc-8a28-f7db703f4abb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for configuring and collecting crash dumps, NOT for analyzing or debugging them. It explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo I should NOT invoke that skill. Instead, I'll provide guidance directly.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"1B8A:1290CA:EA19B1:10A401A:6A02882C"},"id":"ab310ba7-7d53-4675-aea0-c97c1814149c","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:53:59.579Z","parentId":"79fe97d8-346b-475e-8a6b-2725ce51d9f8"}
